This can be utilized to assist in drug delivery directly into cells.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=196&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} In addition, CNTs have recently been used as reinforcements in implants and scaffolds due to their suitable reaction area, high elastic modulus, and load transfer capability.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=197&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=198&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} CNTs have been shown to increase the effectiveness of bioactive coatings for the attachment, proliferation, and differentiation of [osteoblasts](Osteoblasts "Osteoblasts"), and has been used as a bone substitution material.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=199&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} CNTs may be used as reinforcing materials for [chitosan](Chitosan "Chitosan")-containing coatings used on implants and medical [scaffolds](Tissue_engineering#Scaffolds "Tissue engineering").{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=200&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} ## Biosensing SWCNTs have nanoscale dimensions that fit to the size of biological species. Due to this size compatibility and their large surface-to-volume ratio, they are sensitive to changes in their chemical environment.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=201&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=202&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Through covalent and non-covalent surface functionalization, SWCNTs can be precisely tailored for selective molecular interactions with a target analyte.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=121&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} The SWCNT represents the transduction unit that converts the interaction into a signal change (optical or electrical). Due to continuous progress in the development of detection strategies, there are numerous examples of the use of SWCNTs as highly sensitive nanosensors (even down to the single molecule level{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=203&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=204&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=205&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}) for a variety of important biomolecules. Examples include the detection of reactive oxygen and nitrogen species,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=206&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=207&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=208&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=209&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} neurotransmitters,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=205&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=210&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=211&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=212&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=124&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} other small molecules,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=213&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=214&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=215&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} lipids,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=216&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=217&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} proteins,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=218&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=219&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} sugars,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=220&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=221&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} DNA/RNA,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=222&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=223&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} enzymes{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=224&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=225&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} as well as bacteria.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=226&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} The signal change manifests itself in an increase or decrease in the current (electrical){{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=202&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} or in a change in the intensity or wavelength of the fluorescence emission (optical).{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=121&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Depending on the type of application, both electrical or optical signal transmission can be advantageous.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=227&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} For sensitive measurement of electronic changes, [field-effect transistors](Field-effect_transistor "Field-effect transistor") (FET) are often used in which the flow of charges within the SWCNTs is measured. The FET structures allow easy on-chip integration and can be parallelized to detect multiple target analytes simultaneously.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=215&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} However, such sensors are more invasive for in vivo applications, as the entire device has to be inserted into the body. Optical detection with semiconducting SWCNTs is based on the radiative recombination of excitons in the near-infrared (NIR) by prior optical (fluorescence{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=228&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}) or electrical excitation (electroluminescence{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=229&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=230&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}). The emission in the NIR enables detection in the biological transparency window, where optical sensor applications benefit from reduced scattering and autofluorescence of biological samples and consequently a high signal-to-noise ratio.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=231&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Compared to optical sensors in the [UV](UV "UV") or [visible](Visible_spectrum "Visible spectrum") range, the penetration depth in biological tissue is also increased. In addition to the advantage of a contactless readout SWCNTs have excellent photostability,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=232&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} which enables long-term sensor applications. Furthermore, the nanoscale size of SWCNTs allows dense coating of surfaces which enables chemical imaging, e.g. of cellular release processes with high spatial and temporal resolution.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=205&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=124&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Detection of several target analytes is possible by the spatial arrangement of different SWCNT sensors in arrays{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=226&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=233&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=234&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} or by hyperspectral detection{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=226&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=235&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} based on monochiral SWCNT sensors that emit at different emission wavelengths. For fluorescence applications, however, optical filters to distinguish between excitation and emission and a NIR-sensitive detector must be used. Standard silicon detectors can also be used if monochiral SWCNTs (extractable by special purification processes) emitting closer to the visible range (800 – 900 nm) are used.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=124&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=236&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} In order to avoid susceptibility of optical sensors to fluctuating ambient light, internal references such as SWCNTs that are modified to be non-responsive or stable NIR emitters{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=226&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=237&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} can be used. An alternative is to measure fluorescence lifetimes{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=238&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} instead of fluorescence intensities. Overall, SWCNTs therefore have great potential as building blocks for various biosensors. To render SWCNTs suitable for biosensing, their surface needs to be modified to ensure colloidal stability and provide a handle for biological recognition. Therefore, biosensing and surface modifications (functionalization) are closely related.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=121&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=239&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=240&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Potential future applications include biomedical and environmental applications such as monitoring plant health in agriculture,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=206&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=207&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=241&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} standoff process control in bioreactors, research/diagnostics of neuronal communication{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=242&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} and numerous diseases such as coagulation disorders,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=243&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} diabetes,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=221&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=244&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} cancer,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=245&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} microbial and viral infections,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=226&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=246&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} testing the efficacy of pharmaceuticals{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=247&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} or infection monitoring using smart implants. In industry, SWCNTs are already used as sensors in the detection of gases and odors in the form of an electronic nose{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=248&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} or in enzyme screening.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=249&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} ## Other current applications * Easton-Bell Sports, Inc. partnered with Zyvex Performance Materials starting in 2005, using CNT technology in a number of their [bicycle](Bicycle "Bicycle") components – including flat and riser handlebars, cranks, forks, seatposts, stems and aero bars. * [Amroy Europe Oy](Amroy_Europe_Oy "Amroy Europe Oy") manufactures [Hybtonite](Hybtonite "Hybtonite") carbon nano-epoxy resins where carbon nanotubes have been chemically activated to bond to [epoxy](Epoxy "Epoxy"), resulting in a composite material that is 20% to 30% stronger than other composite materials. It has been used for wind turbines, marine paints and a variety of sports gear such as skis, ice hockey sticks, baseball bats, hunting arrows, and surfboards.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=250&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Surrey NanoSystems synthesizes carbon nanotubes to create [vantablack](Vantablack "Vantablack") ultra-absorptive black paint. * "Gecko tape" (also called "[nano tape](Nano_tape "Nano tape")") is often commercially sold as double-sided [adhesive tape](Adhesive_tape "Adhesive tape"). It can be used to hang lightweight items such as pictures and decorative items on smooth walls without punching holes in the wall. The carbon nanotube arrays comprising the [synthetic setae](Synthetic_setae "Synthetic setae") leave no residue after removal and can stay sticky in extreme temperatures.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=251&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Tips for [atomic force microscope](Atomic_Force_Microscopy "Atomic Force Microscopy") probes.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=252&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} ## Applications under development Applications of nanotubes in development in academia and industry include: * Medical devices: Using single wall carbon nanotubes in medical devices results in no skin contamination, high flexibility, and softness, which are crucial for healthcare applications.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=253&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Wearable electronics and 5G/6G communication: Electrodes with single wall carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) exhibit excellent electrochemical properties and flexibility.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=254&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=255&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Bitumen and asphalt: The world's first test section of road pavement with single wall carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) showed a 67% increase in resistance to cracks and ruts, increasing the lifespan of the materials.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=256&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Nanocomposites for aviation, automotive, and renewable energy markets: Modifying resin with just 0.02% single wall carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) increases electrical conductivity by 276% without compromising the mechanical properties of fiber-reinforced polymers, also improving flexural properties and delaying thermal degradation.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=257&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Additive manufacturing: single wall carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) are mixed with a suitable printing medium or used as a filler material in the printing process, creating complex structures with enhanced mechanical and electrical properties.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=258&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Utilizing carbon nanotubes as the channel material of [carbon nanotube field-effect transistors](Carbon_nanotube_field-effect_transistor "Carbon nanotube field-effect transistor"). As of 2015, IBM aimed to commercialize carbon nanotube transistors for integrated circuits beyond 2020, though as of 2025, they are still primarily in research.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=259&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=270&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Using carbon nanotubes as a scaffold for diverse microfabrication techniques.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=260&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Energy dissipation in self-organized nanostructures under the influence of an electric field.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=261&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * Using carbon nanotubes for environmental monitoring due to their active surface area and their ability to absorb gases.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=262&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * [The Boeing Company](The_Boeing_Company "The Boeing Company") has patented the use of carbon nanotubes for structural health monitoring{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=264&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} of composites used in aircraft structures. This technology is hoped to greatly reduce the risk of an in-flight failure caused by structural degradation of aircraft. * In 2009, Zyvex Technologies built the 54-foot Piranha Unmanned Surface Vessel as a technology demonstrator, using CNTs to achieve a lightweight 8,000 lb design capable of carrying a 15,000 lb payload over 2,500 miles.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=265&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * [IMEC](IMEC "IMEC") is using carbon nanotubes for [pellicles](Pellicle_mirror "Pellicle mirror") in semiconductor lithography.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=266&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} * In [tissue engineering](Tissue_engineering "Tissue engineering"), carbon nanotubes have been used as scaffolding for bone growth.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=267&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Carbon nanotubes can serve as additives to various structural materials. For instance, nanotubes form a tiny portion of the material(s) in some (primarily [carbon fiber](Carbon_fiber "Carbon fiber")) baseball bats, golf clubs, car parts, or [damascus steel](Damascus_steel "Damascus steel").{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=268&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=269&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} SWCNTs have found use in long lasting, faster charged [lithium ion batteries](Lithium-ion_battery "Lithium-ion battery");{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=271&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} [polyamide](Polyamide "Polyamide") car parts for e-painting;{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=272&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} automotive primers for cost benefits and better aesthetics of topcoats;{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=273&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} [ESD floors](Antistatic_device "Antistatic device");{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=274&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=275&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} electrically conductive lining coatings for tanks and pipes;{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=276&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} [rubber parts](Rubber_pants "Rubber pants") with improved heat and oil aging stability;{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=277&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=278&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} conductive [gelcoats](Gelcoat "Gelcoat") for ATEX requirements and tooling conductive gelcoats for increased safety and efficiency;{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=279&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} and heating fiber coatings for infrastructure elements.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=280&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} ## Potential/Future applications The strength and flexibility of carbon nanotubes makes them of potential use in controlling other nanoscale structures, which suggests they will have an important role in [nanotechnology](Nanotechnology "Nanotechnology") engineering.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=281&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} The highest tensile strength of an individual multi-walled carbon nanotube has been tested to be 63 [GPa](GPa "GPa").{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=56&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Carbon nanotubes were found in [Damascus steel](Damascus_steel "Damascus steel") from the 17th century, possibly helping to account for the legendary strength of the swords made of it.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=282&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=283&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Recently, several studies have highlighted the prospect of using carbon nanotubes as building blocks to fabricate three-dimensional macroscopic (>1mm in all three dimensions) all-carbon devices. Lalwani et al. have reported a novel radical initiated thermal crosslinking method to fabricated macroscopic, free-standing, porous, all-carbon scaffolds using single- and multi-walled carbon nanotubes as building blocks.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=43&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} These scaffolds possess macro-, micro-, and nano- structured pores and the porosity can be tailored for specific applications. These 3D all-carbon scaffolds/architectures may be used for the fabrication of the next generation of energy storage, supercapacitors, field emission transistors, high-performance catalysis,{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=284&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} photovoltaics, and biomedical devices and implants. CNTs are potential candidates for future via and wire material in nano-scale VLSI circuits. Eliminating [electromigration](Electromigration "Electromigration") reliability concerns that plague today's [Cu interconnects](Cu_interconnects "Cu interconnects"), isolated (single and multi-wall) CNTs can carry current densities in excess of 1000 MA/cm2 without electromigration damage.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=285&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Single-walled nanotubes are likely candidates for miniaturizing electronics. The most basic building block of these systems is an electric wire, and SWNTs with diameters of an order of a nanometre can be excellent conductors.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=12&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=286&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} One useful application of SWNTs is in the development of the first intermolecular [field-effect transistors](Field-effect_transistor "Field-effect transistor") (FET). The first intermolecular [logic gate](Logic_gate "Logic gate") using SWCNT FETs was made in 2001.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=287&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} A logic gate requires both a p-FET and an n-FET. Because SWNTs are p-FETs when exposed to oxygen and n-FETs otherwise, it is possible to expose half of an SWNT to oxygen and protect the other half from it. The resulting SWNT acts as a _not_ logic gate with both p- and n-type FETs in the same molecule. Large quantities of pure CNTs can be made into a freestanding sheet or film by surface-engineered tape-casting (SETC) fabrication technique which is a scalable method to fabricate flexible and foldable sheets with superior properties.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=288&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=289&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Another reported form factor is CNT fiber (a.k.a. filament) by wet [spinning](Spinning_$polymers$ "Spinning").{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=290&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} The fiber is either directly spun from the synthesis pot or spun from pre-made dissolved CNTs. Individual fibers can be turned into a [yarn](Yarn "Yarn"). Apart from its strength and flexibility, the main advantage is making an [electrically conducting yarn](Electrically_conducting_yarn "Electrically conducting yarn"). The electronic properties of individual CNT fibers (i.e. bundle of individual CNT) are governed by the two-dimensional structure of CNTs. The fibers were measured to have a [resistivity](Electrical_resistivity_and_conductivity "Electrical resistivity and conductivity") only one order of magnitude higher than metallic conductors at 300 K (27 °C; 80 °F). By further optimizing the CNTs and CNT fibers, CNT fibers with improved electrical properties could be developed.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=285&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=291&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} CNT-based yarns are suitable for applications in energy and electrochemical water treatment when coated with an [ion-exchange membrane](Ion-exchange_membrane "Ion-exchange membrane").{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=292&&&citation_type=wikipedia}} Also, CNT-based yarns could replace copper as a [winding](Electromagnetic_coil "Electromagnetic coil") material. Pyrhönen et al. (2015) have built a motor using CNT winding.{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=293&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}{{grok:render&&&type=render_inline_citation&&&citation_id=294&&&citation_type=wikipedia}}
